text: I think more people should consider going no AC. If you see it as 3 months of sauna each year where you sweat off heavy metals and stuff all day you can probably justify it to yourself. The pleasure you get from a cold gin and tonic in July is superior to having climate controls.

Same goes for car AC, driving with the windows open and the summer air hitting you and drinking a bunch of cold Ayran feels nicer than having the AC on and the windows up, makes you feel alive. I assume it takes some time getting used to it if you are used to ACs.

The difference between someone intellectually disciplined and intellectually undisciplined is standing firm in your beliefs when normies adopt them. Sm1 posted a videos of turbonormies at a "raw milk party". It does nothing for me. I can watch it on loop for hours w/o flinching.

Any of my personally held convictions and beliefs would sound just as good coming from the mouth of any tiktok influencer as they do in the palace of my mind. I want others to actively embrace my worldview even if they try to drag it down. Anything else is intellectual cowardice.

You often see someone proclaim a stance or idea for years and when others start to adopt it he immediately backs away and starts being pathologically contrarian and naysaying, distancing himself from it. It's natural. But it is a sign of a grave lack of intellectual discipline.

Good example of the skill of being there for others when they need it: once back in the day on League of Legends a pro player (I think Doublelift) was depressed and wanted to off himself and Trick2G spent the entire night just talking to him on Skype or whatever we had back then.

Didn't make a show of it or tell anyone about it (the depressed guy talked about it later IIRC), just sat there talking to him for one night and making sure he's not alone. Type of guy who always makes sure others get home safe from a night out. Really, really admirable to me.

Sacrificing a night of sleep to make sure someone is ok is a thing that is always worth to do and that will always be repaid back to you by Providence one day. "So then let us not sleep, as others do, but let us keep awake and be sober." 1 Thessalonians 5:6

I think he agrees with my belief that high IQ fraud is an oxymoron and people are far better at deceiving themselves than consciously doing it to others. I'd bet that model Anna Nicole Smith that married a 90 year old billionaire for his money ended up actually loving him.

It's similar to how when people jokingly call each other each other's girlfriend or boyfriend they always end up dating for real soon afterwards. I just cannot imagine most people having the ability to separate themselves from their words and actions or that level of abstraction.

And the people who have the intelligence required to detach themselves from their actions and words and consciously dissociate their true inner self from their outer life will have that very same intelligence soon force them into being all so moral and benevolent. It's a paradox.

For You Pagers love talking about "we need to bring back bullying dawg", but the only thing that puts the fear of the Lord in you like nothing else and actually alters your personality for the better is a real encounter with death, like surviving a forest fire or a bad car crash.

E.g. I remember he went on an expedition to some deep sewers with a population of mentally ill homeless people there, could easily get stabbed, poked with a needle, etc. Most would not be that courageous. I think an encounter with close death cultivates both chivalry and bravery.

Nemets is a good example. He's talked about falling off a cliff and being really hurt, thinking he was about to die in seconds, semi-consciously checking his body for major bleeding. He's both very polite and courteous, and also fearless, not scared to walk into dangerous places.
